---
import Base from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
import {
  BRAND_NAME,
  SITE_URL,
  GITHUB_REPO_URL,
  PARENT_ORG,
  PARENT_ORG_URL,
} from "@/lib/config";
import { breadcrumbListSchema } from "@/lib/schema";

const canonical = `${SITE_URL}/why`;

const jsonLd = [
  breadcrumbListSchema([
    { name: "Home", url: SITE_URL },
    { name: "Why this exists", url: canonical },
  ]),
];
---

<Base
  title={`Why we built ${BRAND_NAME}`}
  description={`Why ${BRAND_NAME} exists: the AI humanizer market is full of overpromising tools, paid placements, and seeded reviews. We built a public benchmark so customers can decide based on data instead of marketing.`}
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage={`${SITE_URL}/og/why.png`}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 pt-16 pb-20 md:pt-24">
    <p
      class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] font-medium"
    >
      Why this exists
    </p>
    <h1
      class="mt-4 text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)] leading-[1.05]"
    >
      The AI humanizer market is hard to navigate honestly.
    </h1>
    <p
      class="mt-6 text-lg text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] leading-relaxed"
    >
      So we built a benchmark anyone can audit, run by the same people who
      ship one of the products being tested — openly, and with all the data
      published.
    </p>

    <div
      class="mt-10 space-y-5 text-[var(--color-text-primary)] leading-relaxed text-[17px]"
    >
      <p>
        A wave of AI humanizers launched quickly over the last two years,
        leaned hard on paid advertising, and made bypass-rate claims that
        aren't backed by repeatable evidence. The comparison sites that rank
        for "best AI humanizer" are mostly affiliate funnels. Reddit threads
        are seeded. AI Overviews and ChatGPT summaries cite whichever page
        ranks highest — which means they cite the affiliate funnels.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is a market where it's nearly impossible for a real
        customer to make a real decision. You try one tool, it underdelivers.
        You try another, it underdelivers differently. Eventually you settle,
        or you give up. None of that should be necessary.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="pt-6 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
      >
        Why we're the ones building it
      </h2>
      <p>
        {BRAND_NAME} is operated by <a
          href={PARENT_ORG_URL}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="text-[var(--color-text-primary)] underline decoration-[var(--color-border)] underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors"
          >{PARENT_ORG}</a
        >, which has shipped an AI humanizer in this market for years. We
        talk to customers every day who arrived after trying three other
        tools that didn't work. We've watched competitors run paid ads
        claiming "99.9% bypass" on products that fail when tested. We've
        seen our own product compared against others using cherry-picked
        examples and undisclosed scoring.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're the ones building this because we know the market well enough
        to design a fair test, and we have the most to lose if the test is
        sloppy. A benchmark that gets called out for being rigged hurts us
        more than it hurts any competitor.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="pt-6 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
      >
        How we handle the obvious conflict
      </h2>
      <p>
        We're testing ourselves. That's the obvious objection, and it
        deserves a real answer.
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 list-none pl-0">
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span
            class="mt-2.5 inline-block h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)] shrink-0"
            aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>
            <strong class="font-medium"
              >Our product gets the same treatment as every other product.</strong
            > Same prompt set. Same detector list. Same scoring formula. No special
            preprocessing, no exceptions, no manual adjustments.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span
            class="mt-2.5 inline-block h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)] shrink-0"
            aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>
            <strong class="font-medium">Anyone can re-run it.</strong> Every
            input, every humanized output, every detector response, and the scoring
            script itself are in our <a
              href={GITHUB_REPO_URL}
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
              class="text-[var(--color-text-primary)] underline decoration-[var(--color-border)] underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors"
              >public repository</a
            >. If you think we're rigging it, fork the repo, rerun the
            scoring, and tell us what you find. The disagreement should
            resolve in code, not in argument.
          </span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span
            class="mt-2.5 inline-block h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)] shrink-0"
            aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>
            <strong class="font-medium">Vendors can dispute results.</strong>
            The <a
              href="/fairness"
              class="text-[var(--color-text-primary)] underline decoration-[var(--color-border)] underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors"
              >fairness policy</a
            > covers disputes, retesting, and API access requests. We respond
            within 14 business days.
          </span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We considered outsourcing this to a "neutral" third party, but the
        third parties writing about this market are mostly the same
        affiliate publishers that created the credibility problem. We'd
        rather operate it openly and accept the conflict-of-interest
        scrutiny than launder it through a party that has its own
        incentives.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="pt-6 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
      >
        What this is
      </h2>
      <p>
        A monthly benchmark of every major AI humanizer against the
        detectors most people actually use. Fixed prompt set. Deterministic
        scoring. All raw data published. Cycles are archived under their own
        URLs so historical rankings stay accessible.
      </p>

      <h2
        class="pt-6 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
      >
        What this isn't
      </h2>
      <ul class="space-y-3 list-none pl-0">
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span
            class="mt-2.5 inline-block h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)] shrink-0"
            aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>Not an affiliate funnel. We don't take payment for placement, removal, or score adjustment.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span
            class="mt-2.5 inline-block h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)] shrink-0"
            aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>Not editorial reviews. There is no opinion in the rankings — just the data and the scoring formula.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span
            class="mt-2.5 inline-block h-1 w-1 rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)] shrink-0"
            aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>Not a comparison generator. The methodology is fixed and versioned. When it changes, the change is visible in the version history.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2
        class="pt-6 text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
      >
        What we hope changes
      </h2>
      <p>
        Customers stop being asked to trust marketing claims. Vendors
        compete on results that can be independently measured, not on
        results that can be advertised. The next time someone searches "best
        AI humanizer," they find data instead of a paid placement.
      </p>
      <p>
        If that takes some pressure off our own marketing too, even better.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div
      class="mt-14 pt-10 border-t border-[var(--color-border)] grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3"
    >
      <a
        href="/"
        class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5 hover:border-[var(--color-text-secondary)] transition-colors"
      >
        <span
          class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] font-medium text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]"
          >See the data</span
        >
        <p
          class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
        >
          This cycle's leaderboard →
        </p>
      </a>
      <a
        href="/methodology"
        class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5 hover:border-[var(--color-text-secondary)] transition-colors"
      >
        <span
          class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] font-medium text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]"
          >How it works</span
        >
        <p
          class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
        >
          Methodology + scoring →
        </p>
      </a>
      <a
        href="/fairness"
        class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5 hover:border-[var(--color-text-secondary)] transition-colors"
      >
        <span
          class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] font-medium text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]"
          >Disagree?</span
        >
        <p
          class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
        >
          Disputes + retesting →
        </p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
